[normal]Q375 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hywel[bold] Williams:[bold] Good afternoon. Both Gerry 
[normal]Holtham
[normal] and the Silk Commission came out against the lockstep. The First Minister, giving evidence to us down in 
[normal]Cardiff
[normal], said that it would be an immense straitjacket
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]he also 
[normal]went as far as to say that it would make the power unusable. Indeed, that was the evidence given to us by other witnesses, both people from the world of business and from political studies. Do you accept that the Welsh Government would be unlikely to call a referendum because of their perceived difficulties in using this power?
[normal]Mr Jones[bold]: 
[normal]I have to say, Mr Chairman, that that really will be a matter for the Welsh Government
[normal],
[normal] because, as you know, we propose to devolve the competence to the Welsh Government to call a referendum at such time as 
[normal]they consider
[normal] appropriate. But I disagree entirely with the suggestion that the powers proposed are unusable. I think that the powers proposed are extremely desirable. Frankly, too much focus has been placed on the
[normal] issue of variation—of varying the rates.
[normal]The important thing about the proposed devolution of income tax powers is, first, that it renders the Welsh Government far more accountable to the people of 
[normal]Wales
[normal]. It would provide that almost half of the income tax raised in 
[normal]Wales
[normal] would be spent, if you like, by the Welsh Government. I think it is very important to introduce that level of accountability into the process. Importantly
[normal],
[normal] too, it would act as a strong incentive to the Welsh Government to grow the Welsh economy
[normal],
[normal] because, clearly, the more the economy improves
[normal],
[normal] the more likely it 
[normal]is that the tax take from the devolved eleme
[normal]nt of income tax would increase—
[normal]and that is desirable as well. Thirdly
[normal]—
[normal]and I think possibly, in the eyes of some, most importantly
[normal]—
[normal]it would provide a significantly enhanced income stream against which the Welsh Government could borrow. So
[normal], while on the face of the Bill
[normal] we have £500 million
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]worth
[normal] of borrowing powers, which is actually more than the Welsh Government should have strictly if we have regard only to the devolved small taxes, 
[normal]it
[normal] could increase to around £1 billion once the income stream from the income tax is there. But, to complete my answer, I 
[normal]actually 
[normal]believe that 
[normal]Wales
[normal] should be ambitious
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]I believe 
[normal]that it could give a strong competitive advantage to 
[normal]Wales
[normal] if they were to go for a modest reduction in the level of tax that they levy on the people of 
[normal]Wales
[normal].
[normal]Mr [bold]Gauke[bold]: 
[normal]Can I just add
[normal],
[normal] with regard to the lockstep
[normal],
[normal] that it is worth pointing out that our view, as a Government
[normal]—
[normal]and this applies across the United Kingdom
[normal]—is 
[normal]that, in terms of the differentiation between rates, we do believe that that is something that should be determined on a UK basis in Westminster elections
[normal]?
[normal] I think, in a way, putting aside for the moment the merits or otherwise of the shadow Chancellor
[normal]’
[normal]s announcement at the weekend, none the less tha
[normal]t does demonstrate the degree in
[normal] which the gaps between rates is a very important issue that should apply across the 
[normal]United Kingdom
[normal]. That, as I say, is the approach that we have taken in 
[normal]Scotland
[normal],
[normal] and we believe that the same case applies with 
[normal]Wales
[normal]. 
[normal]There is also an issue, looking at this, in terms of not causing any detriment to the public finances collectively in the 
[normal]United Kingdom
[normal]. One possible result of allowing a different rate to be set for the additional rate is that 
[normal]Wales
[normal], for example, might decide that the rates set in 
[normal]Westminster
[normal] are too high. They may be right in making that judgment, potentially, and in those circumstances we see a degree of tax competition, trying to get people to move from, say, 
[normal]England
[normal] to 
[normal]Wales
[normal]. That throws up a number of issues, but one consequence of that is likely to be a detriment to the overall public finances in the 
[normal]UK
[normal]. So we are nervous about that. 
